      <section title="Introduction">
         <t>Feed Service Management (FSM) is a decentralized protocol for organizing, managing, and persisting client-side state for large numbers of feed-based Web services. This document describes the motivations, data models, and protocol interactions for FSM servers and clients. In particular, it specifies how clients create and modify service descriptions stored on an FSM server, how they should retrieve and use such service descriptions, and how these interactions apply across multiple FSM servers, possibly operated by completely independent entities.</t>
         <section title="RESTful Web Services">
            <t>A growing number of web applications offer APIs and web services, as means to share data and interoperate with other services and devices.   Many such services expose RESTful APIs, with one of the prevalent protocols for designing standards-based RESTful APIs being Atom and AtomPub. </t>
         </section>
         <section title="Feed-based Services">
            <t>iTunes podcasts, for example, are enclosed audio files delivered as a service via feeds, albeit wrapped within the Apple iTunes client. Large web content management systems, like Wordpress or Blogger, offer full-featured read-write Web services for publishing, consuming, and managing content. In application areas such as the Web of Things, a large number of sensors, appliances, and other everyday objects may emit data streams, made accessible on the Web as real-time data feeds. Generally speaking, any federated and decentralized ecosystem of producers and consumers of information services can be modeled as a feed-based architecture.</t>
         </section>
